Create Pipeline for predicted house price based on Easting, Northing and average floor area.¶

In [36]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor as NN
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, make_scorer
mae = make_scorer(mean_absolute_error, greater_is_better=False)
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [37]:
price = hp['price']/1000.0
In [38]:
pipe = Pipeline([('zscores',StandardScaler()),('NNreg',NN())])

opt_pipe = GridSearchCV(
    estimator = pipe,
    scoring = mae,
    param_grid = {
        'NNreg__n_neighbors':range(1,35),
        'NNreg__weights':['uniform','distance'],
        'NNreg__p':[1,2]})

opt_pipe.fit(hp[['east','north','fl_area']],price)
Out[38]:

A 3-D plot of the house price for floor areas of 75 square metres.¶

In [54]:
def surf3d(pipe_model,fl_area):
    east_mesh, north_mesh = np.meshgrid(
        np.linspace(505000,555800,100),
        np.linspace(158400,199900,100))
    fl_mesh = np.zeros_like(east_mesh)
    fl_mesh[:,:] = fl_area
    grid_predictor_vars = np.array([east_mesh.ravel(),north_mesh.ravel(),fl_mesh.ravel()]).T
    hp_pred = pipe_model.predict(grid_predictor_vars)
    hp_mesh = hp_pred.reshape(east_mesh.shape)
    fig = pl.figure()
    ax = Axes3D(fig)
    ax.plot_surface(east_mesh, north_mesh, hp_mesh, rstride=1, cstride=1, cmap='YlOrBr',lw=0.01)
    ax.set_xlabel('Easting')
    ax.set_ylabel('Northing')
    ax.set_zlabel('Price')
    pl.show()
    return

Report¶

The following report seeks to illustrate the technique used to construct each 3-D plot of house price through Easting & Northing location, from machine learning pipeline right through to data visualization. We will also delve into what differences are exhibited across price for varying floor areas, and what these differences mean in the overall assessment of each plot, as well as touching on the subtleties and nuances that exist in K nearest neighbor predictive models.

I began by importing all necessary packages; numpy, pandas and matplotlib, as well as importing the housing dataset. I decided to use the pipeline technique, as it is the smoothest way to create the plots, and will likely serve me well in the future, thus I wanted to get to grips with it here. Several functions from the sk.learn package were employed to create and execute the pipeline. The first of which was StandardScaler, which allows us to convert variables into z-scores, ensuring a common scale is observed, whilst still retaining the same variance in their relationship. Several different machine learning algorithms were at our disposal, however, k-nearest neighbours seemed most appropriate as house prices are often intrinsically linked with location. Thus, we imported the KNeighborsRegressor function, abbreviated as NN. Both functions StandardScaler & KNeighborsRegressor are passed through the pipeline argument as a list of tuples, we name this object pipe. Rather than trying to tune the parameters myself, I opted for a cross-validation grid-search, to optimize results. As the sklearn package doesnt directly provide a cross-validation function, we had to create a scoring object. I chose to use the mean absolute error as the empirical scorer. Other arguments passed through the GridSearchCV function include; estimator specifying the machine learning algorithm, and param_grid a dictionary of tuning parameters to cycle through until the combination with the lowest MAE is found. The outcome is stored in the opt_pipe object, before further .fit and .predict methods are applied. The k nearest neighbors pipeline was now complete.

The next task at hand pertains to the visualization and description of results. We begin by creating a mesh grid as our canvas, covering 100 x 100 points within the specified Easting and Northing Range. A third parameter, floor area is added. Things become a bit tricky as the predict method, essential to plotting our parameter space is only accessible by unravelling each variable into a single dimensional array. Following some necessary ravelling and re-shaping, the data was wrangled inot a grid format, capable of carrying house price predictions. Finally, we add a function to automate the surface drawing, passing through the KNN pipeline model as well as a fixed floor area as arguments. The function is reproduced for each instance of the 3D plot.

In analysing the results of the plots, we begin by comparing price through average floor area, and Easting, Northing locations. The plot illustrates a few small peaks spread out across the grid, aswell as a sharp increase clustered in one area. What we can deduce from this plot is that floor space is not quite a strong predictor of house price, rather, the location the dwelling exists exercises more action on its price value.

Whats particularly interesting is the variation in the prediction surface as we analyse dwellings with different floor areas. At 75m , we observe a sharp rise in cluster of data in the middle, an area we can assume to label as affluent. The areas outside this cluster also appear to have similar prices, or at least exhibit less variation in the prediction surface. By the same token, at the other end of the scale, dwellings with a floor area covering 250m convey the sharpest increase in price. Again, this acute ascent is most prominent in the area emanating from 515000 Easting and 190000 Northing. And most notably, its actually average sized homes that exhibit the most uniformity in price through location.

To summarise our findings at different levels of floor area, Easting and Northing exert varying degrees of influence on the prediction of price. That is to say, for dwellings at each end of the floor area scale, Easting and Northing play a slightly less important role in predicting price than for average sized homes.

That said, there is an underlying issue of economies of scale here. Another reason for little to no variation in prediction surface for Easting and Northing at the premium end of the market, is that larger homes, are by nature, built in more affluent areas. We are far less likely to see an eight bedroomed Victorian mansion built in between blocks of highrise flats, correct? I would argue that the lack of spatial variation is owed to the almost exclusive ownership of larger homes by the affluent. Thus I think any assumption made vis--vis Easting and Northing homes playing a lesser role in house prices might be ill-fated.

It must be noted that there is a potential for bias within this data, such is the bounded region with which data exists. Lets bear in mind that the k nearest neighbor model is optimized at 16 neighbors. Thus, any house at the edge of the Easting Northing boundary that we have arbitrarily defined, can only have neighbors internal to the dataset, even though there may well be neighbors closer in real life. This means that for illustrated models above, we must discount some level of credence from how low the house prices are at the edge of the plots. A good example of this is seen in the prediction surface for houses average 250m floor area. In the right corner of the plot, for houses situated in 540000-550000 Easting and 190000-200000 Northing, there is clearly very little data with which to form K nearest neighbors predictions. What we are left with is this flat, block-like surface, devoid of color or detail. I think this only serves to further augment my previous notion regarding the exclusivity of larger homes to affluent areas which has ultimately provided us with a skewed illustration.
